just_use trick.go

# label: TINY
# role: encodes domain knowledge

Declares the Trick + Play interfaces that every trick in this package
implements. Plugin shape: stateless singleton trick (zero-sized struct),
FindPlays returns concrete Plays, each Play carries its own captured
state (no closures) and knows how to Apply against a board.

**Divergence from TS:** TS's apply(board) mutates in place and returns
the hand cards. Go returns (newBoard, played) — a pure reducer shape.

**Apply-time revalidation is still a per-trick responsibility.**
Individual tricks (e.g. pair_peel, loose_card_play) re-check validity
before committing — board state can drift between FindPlays and Apply
if multiple plays are queued. An Apply that can't complete returns
(board, nil/[]) to signal refusal; see `Trick.claude` in Elm for the
matching contract. What Go drops is TS's blanket diff-revalidation
scaffolding, not the per-trick sanity checks.
